scenes.label: *from_AC_03_04b
texts: Huh? This looks legit, doesn't it? It is, right?
I made it back to right after the whole incident began.
Woo! Praise from Takaoka?! Feels good, man! I guess I'm becoming a better info broker!
But I praise you all the time...
Hey, I like your praise too! You're my sweet, sweet gf.
Now, about the thing Takaoka praised me for...
I interrupted him and darted out of Symphony.
I passed Oz's place and followed the path leading to the MTIL.
If Oz'd left his office, he must've come through here.
I saw a red vintage car a short distance ahead.
Next, I ran a search based on its appearance. The car was from 1958.
It was ancient...and that could only mean one thing.
I got a little closer and saw that Oz was driving the left-hand drive car.
I shouted with my thumb held out.
Sorry, but I got no time to play with you right now.
You're going to the MTIL to deal with the 302 problem, right? I'm gonna help too, so I wanna find out more about it.
I got no idea what you're talkin' about.
Don't bullshit me! Just let me in!
I drove my graper in front of his car, forcing him to pull over.
I hopped into the passenger seat before he could argue.
It had one large seat at the front instead of two separate ones. I'd never seen a car like this.
Don't soil my ride. It's a rental.
Oz started driving again. He looked pretty disgruntled.
Huh? You're actually driving it manually?
Can't get too dependent on machines. I don't wanna end up rusty.
I felt safe swerving in front of him on my graper 'cause I thought this thing was self-driving.
But since Oz was driving it himself, I'd actually risked my life back there.
And Oz was still driving it manually...
I scrambled to get my seatbelt on.
As we made our way to the MTIL, I went on the internet to grab some more info about 302.
Oh. There's a clip from inside the cabin.
It was the same as when Momo set up the connection last time.
Inside the plane was total chaos. The passengers were either anxious or yelling in fear.
Oz, we got some new info.
I shared the feed with the tablet that was where the sat-nav would usually be.
There's no armed hijackers or anything.
Oz looked at the tablet and froze.
You don't approve of me going into someone's device? But it's an emergen—
Oz let go of the wheel.
I quickly activated self-driving through my tablet.
What are you doing?! We could crash!
Feeling my voice rise, I looked at him.

scenes.label: *dummy2
texts: Oz was clutching his head and looking down.
He was sweating buckets and his eyes were open wide.
I hid the feed from inside the plane, but he was still in distress.
It looked like something had scared him, and sent him into a state of panic.
Please...! Don't lock me in here...!
I shook his shoulder as hard as I could.
The light started coming back to his eyes.
Oz checked his pockets and, with shaking hands, took out some kind of medicine capsule.
He cracked it open and poured the powder inside onto the dashboard. Next, he took out a small straw and sucked the powder up through his nose.

scenes.label: *chk_mouth
texts: His breathing was still labored, but he was calming down.
You got some kinda chronic disease?
This is what happens when I...remember it...
Oh, so he lost it 'cause that cabin clip reminded him of the accident.
That's just how it is for adults. We all got issues.
A suited man was waiting for us in the MTIL parking lot.
It was Oz's friend. He worked for the <tips,40,JCAB>.
Both airband and the STS are unusable right now.
And there are no other channels?
Just like Oz had said before I Loaded.
We trusted your advice. The forced deactivation of the STS has been postponed.
We're still looking for a solution, but for now, we have nothing.
Just in case, I ran a face search on him to find his social media accounts.
Finding his name was laughably easy. It was Yutaka Seo.
There were a few email addresses that fit the bill...
I looked over his most recent emails, while feeling concerned that government workers had such crappy security.
...Nothing to get excited about here either.
Like I said before, postponing is just a temporary measure. If you've got no solid plan at this point, you might as well deactivate it.
That's true, but I don't believe it's an option.
The people at the top are disinclined to change the situation. They approved of one of my propositions, but I doubt they would another.
So they're okay with letting those people die?! Turning off the STS could save them!
There was no guarantee, and it could have been a trap set by Cicada, but it was better than doing nothing.
Letting them die...? Yes, I suppose they are.
My fist was raised before I knew it...
Oz grabbed my shoulder before I could take a swing.
We're not done with that bastard yet!
I argued, but he still took me behind the car.
If you're just gonna get in my way, then beat it.
Huh? How am I gettin' in your way?
I get that you're mad 'cause the MTIL ain't taking this as seriously as they should.
But taking it out on him won't fix shit. All you're gonna do is lose me a source for future incidents.
So you're gonna let people die for the sake of the future?!
That's one way to put it, yeah.
Leave the government people to me, and go do what you're good at.
It pissed me off, but he was right.
I wouldn't get much info by beating up some idiots who weren't even looking at the present.

scenes.label: *load
texts: Hey, now you know a little more about how society works.
Oz went back to his source.
Coming to the MTIL had really set me back. Even if I got to work now, I wouldn't be able to prevent the plane crash.

scenes.label: *select1
texts: Yeah. I'll go back and think of a way to set up a new channel.

scenes.label: *notload_S1
texts: I need to figure out how to configure a new channel.
